WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:26.990
&gt;&gt; Anne E. McLean: Good
evening, I'm Anne McLean

00:00:26.990 --> 00:00:29.220
from the Library's Concert Office.

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:32.220
We're presenting tonight a
wonderfully rich evening of music

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:35.990
by Czech composers, Antonin
Dvorak and Bohuslav Martinu

00:00:35.990 --> 00:00:38.850
from the excellent
Pavel Haas Quartet.

00:00:38.850 --> 00:00:41.270
It's very unusual to have on offer

00:00:41.270 --> 00:00:45.970
in one concert both the Dvorak
American Quartet Opus 96

00:00:45.970 --> 00:00:49.220
and also the D Minor
Quartet Opus 34.

00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:53.030
And we are especially pleased to
be able to preface this concert

00:00:53.030 --> 00:00:56.220
with this lecture by Michael
Beckerman who's an authority

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:58.960
on Czech composers and
Eastern European music,

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:01.160
among other subjects.

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:05.230
Dr. Beckman was awarded the
prestigious [inaudible] medal

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:10.200 position:56%
from the Czech Republic and he is a
laureate of the Czech Music Council.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:14.470
It's a pleasure really for us to
welcome him back to the library.

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:17.570
He is the Carroll and Milton
Petrie professor of music

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:21.320
at New York University and the
author of benchmark studies

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:23.710
on these composers we'll
be hearing tonight,

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:28.730
including one fascinating book
called New Worlds of Dvorak,

00:01:28.730 --> 00:01:32.330
Searching in America for
the Composer's Inner Life.

00:01:32.330 --> 00:01:36.080
And that book we have available
for sale in our anteroom tonight.

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:39.620
He's also the editor of
Dvorak and His World.

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:42.510
So let me just say also
that I wanted to mention

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:45.910 position:56%
if you're really interested in these
subjects, please check out a lecture

00:01:45.910 --> 00:01:48.740
by Dr. Beckman that
is now already online

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:52.130
on our website Dvorak
in the New World.

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:58.770 position:56%
He lectured here a few years ago and
this is on our website www.LOC.gov

00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:02.460
and this lecture examines the
role of African-American sources

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:05.270
in the conception of
an American music.

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:08.510
So please help me welcome
Michael Beckman.

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:15.100
[ Applause ]

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:16.990 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Michael Beckerman: Thank you,
thank you for the love introduction,

00:02:16.990 --> 00:02:21.490
I'm delighted to be back
here at the library.

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:30.480
Well I thought I would begin
by mentioning two composers

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:33.300
who actually aren't on the program.

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.120
I'll begin by playing one.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:03:10.040
[ Music ]

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:15.770
This piece, which sounds like late
Beethoven was actually written

00:03:15.770 --> 00:03:19.050
by a contemporary of
Mozart's named Jakub Jan Ryba.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:22.630
Famous for writing one of
the most popular pieces

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:24.920
in the Czech lands
called the Christmas Mass.

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:30.580
But this [inaudible] quartet was
written long before Beethoven

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:36.730
and I play it to remind us all
that there is really a long

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:41.990 position:56%
and distinguished tradition of Czech
string quartet writing or better

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:46.730
yet a string quartet writing in
what are known as the Czech lands.

00:03:46.730 --> 00:03:53.880
Composers like [inaudible],
the Stamitzs, many others,

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:58.160
Wranitzkys who are contemporaries
of Mozart wrote wonderful quartets.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:03.320
Certainly Smetana in his
contemporaries then Dvorak.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:08.090
The followers of Dvorak Josef
Suk, [inaudible], Novak, Martinu.

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:10.530
There's just a long and
distinguished tradition

00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:19.420
of these composers working in this
medium and it's probably pushing it

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:24.930
to say that somehow this medium is
specifically suited to the Czechs.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:28.450
But there are things about it I
think which points that can be made

00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:30.850
and I'll try to make
them as I go along.

00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:35.220 position:56%
The second composer I'm going to
mention and it would be obvious why,

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:38.970
his works are not being
played, but is Pavel Haas.

00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:43.630 position:56%
Pavel Haas was a wonderful composer,
a student of Janacek's who was

00:04:43.630 --> 00:04:48.440
in Terezin where he wrote several
wonderful pieces and was killed

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:53.200
in Auschwitz in in the in 1945.

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.460
But he was again an
extraordinary figure

00:04:55.460 --> 00:05:00.250
and a wonderful quartet
composer, a student of Janacek's

00:05:00.250 --> 00:05:05.570
who both carried on that particular
Moravian tradition or sub tradition

00:05:05.570 --> 00:05:11.240 position:56%
of Czech string quartets, but also
went very much in his own direction.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:15.890
But we're going to begin
tonight with someone

00:05:15.890 --> 00:05:19.420
from another generation,
certainly not of the Dvorak,

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:22.420
Smetana generation this
is Bohuslav Martinu.

00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:31.870 position:56%
Martinu famously born in a church
tower very high above the small town

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:37.270
of Policka where his father
was a professional fire water

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:39.370
because he was also a shoemaker,

00:05:39.370 --> 00:05:41.950
but you needed more
than one job in Policka.

00:05:41.950 --> 00:05:47.170
And there are a hundred
steps above the church

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:50.410
where the Martinu family
lived in a small room.

00:05:50.410 --> 00:05:56.560
And he came down from the tower
really only at about the age of 10,

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:58.350
went to Prague studied there.

00:05:58.350 --> 00:06:02.070
It was a student after my own
heart because he was thrown

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:07.130
out of school several times
for incorrigible laziness.

00:06:07.130 --> 00:06:14.810
And he decided to go to Paris and
I'll get to why he decided to go

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:18.050
to Paris in a moment,
but I thought I'd begin

00:06:18.050 --> 00:06:22.620
by playing just the opening
of this third string quartet

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.000
which was written in Paris in 1939.

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:46.230
[ Music ]

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:51.180 position:56%
Well anyone who actually is familiar
with Martinu would probably be right

00:06:51.180 --> 00:06:56.620 position:56%
to say this is quite on the
dissonant edge of Martinu's writing.

00:06:56.620 --> 00:07:01.880
Martinu again is in Paris
in 1929, he's in the thrall

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:06.060
of many different composers,
very interested in French notions

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:10.580
of clarity, but also very much
in the thrall of Stravinsky

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:13.440
as one can hear by
these motoric rhythms.

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:18.360
But there is one way in which
Martinu's works tend to differ

00:07:18.360 --> 00:07:21.270
from those of Stravinsky
and many others.

00:07:21.270 --> 00:07:25.690
And you can hear it in the next
passage because what happens

00:07:25.690 --> 00:07:30.510
when this motoric style
slows down a bit.

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:48.050
[ Music ]

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:50.260
So you get, you know, you
get all this I don't know,

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.060
you know, Martinu.

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:58.040
[ Music ]

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:01.290
So you get one of these sort
of little syncopated passages

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:06.110
that at various times quite
specifically seem to refer

00:08:06.110 --> 00:08:11.040
to his notion of something Czech.

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:16.150
But really become part of his
style and this is another I think

00:08:16.150 --> 00:08:19.720
of Martinu who wrote -- by the
time he wrote this it's 1929,

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:24.270 position:56%
he was born in 1890 he's not that
old he's already written 200 pieces.

00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:30.990
Martinu is among the most prolific
composers of the 20th century.

00:08:30.990 --> 00:08:37.030
He wrote, you know, well I once a
wrote an article called How Many

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:40.600
Pieces did Martinu Write because
depending on how you choose

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:44.320
to measure pieces you get
any number from 350 to 600.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.070
You know, is it three
etudes, three pieces

00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:50.350
or is it one piece called three
etude, you know, things like that.

00:08:50.350 --> 00:08:53.770
But he wrote a lot of music and
a lot of extraordinary music.

00:08:53.770 --> 00:08:57.730
And this aspect of his style
is something you can hear even

00:08:57.730 --> 00:08:59.370
in a quite dissonant piece.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:03.460 position:56%
I'll give you a couple of examples
from maybe more famous pieces of his

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:07.040
of how these sort of almost
insect-like textures sort

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:11.790
of give way to this sort of
syncopated sort of Martinu sound.

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:14.360
And in that way again, he
strikes me as very much

00:09:14.360 --> 00:09:17.590
like a painter who
has his own style.

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:20.570
I mean not all Jackson
Pollocks are alike,

00:09:20.570 --> 00:09:21.870
but they're all Jackson Pollocks.

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:24.530
And Martinu has certain
musical fingerprints.

00:09:24.530 --> 00:09:27.510
So this is from the sixth
Symphony much later.

00:09:27.510 --> 00:10:17.460
[ Music ]

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:19.760
So you get these kinds of
sounds and you'll hear that even

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:22.050
in this quartet as he
goes kind of in and out

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:23.960
of these highly dissonant textures,

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:26.480
which open up into
these little windows.

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:29.650
And like a lot of pieces this
quartet ends with a kind of,

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:33.510
I mean a movement ends
with a kind of fanfare.

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:42.600
[ Music ]

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:47.760
Sorry, the second movement of
this quartet is very much a kind

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:52.510
of inward turning lyrical piece
with a lot of viola solos.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:11:20.070
[ Music ]

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:23.050
And it's quite again an
extraordinary movement

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:27.490
that has a much more
consonant center.

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:33.070
The last movement begins like
the first, a kind of really harsh

00:11:33.070 --> 00:11:36.510
and sharp dissonant texture.

00:11:36.510 --> 00:11:48.040
[ Music ]

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:50.960
And again, in the middle
of the movement we get one

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.510
of these little Martinu
windows opening up.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:12:31.300
[ Music ]

00:12:31.300 --> 00:12:34.300
Now this is a Martinu
piece unlike some of them

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:36.450
where there's more dissonance

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:39.060
than you usually get
in one of his pieces.

00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:43.780
And it's tricky for a
long time I thought that

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:47.340
and maybe this was just sort of
self-serving that the piece was

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:53.010
about the consonances and that that
he wasn't as invested aesthetically

00:12:53.010 --> 00:12:55.990
in the dissonances
as he was in those --

00:12:55.990 --> 00:12:58.090
that those moments were
the real Martinu moments,

00:12:58.090 --> 00:12:59.820
but I think that was wrong.

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:04.820
I think they're all Martinu moments
and it's I think an exciting kind

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:09.170 position:56%
of aesthetic experience when you
have again, this level of dissonance

00:13:09.170 --> 00:13:14.550
which is opening up and I'll
make a kind of trite suggestion

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:17.850 position:56%
that I can't sort of stay away from.

00:13:17.850 --> 00:13:22.740
But Martinu did have this very
strange experience of growing

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:27.170
up in this tower and he wrote
about it quite a bit and, you know,

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:30.360
he said I was in the
tower all the time

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:35.990
and in the tower I could always
see these absolutely still

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:37.290
natural forms.

00:13:37.290 --> 00:13:40.170
I could see the fields and
the shapes of the fields

00:13:40.170 --> 00:13:41.810
and the people weren't
really people they were

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:43.880
like little ants or something.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:47.230
And part of me thinks that
this tendency of Martinu is

00:13:47.230 --> 00:13:50.380
to always do this, to always
open out into this sort

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:53.770
of still moment even in
the most dissonant pieces.

00:13:53.770 --> 00:13:56.030
You know, is a part of
him that might be related

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:58.920
to that very special
circumstance in which he grew up,

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.650
you can take that or leave it.

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:02.680
But, you know, I can't discount it

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:06.010
because I think it was
important enough to him.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:11.170
So we're going to hear two
string quartets by Dvorak.

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:21.070
One of the things I thought
of titling this talk was well

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:27.860 position:56%
if we call Dvorak's Opus 96 the
American quartet what should we call

00:14:27.860 --> 00:14:30.090
the other quartets?

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:35.540
Should we call Martinu's the
Parisian, the Parisian Tower.

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:42.170
And what do we call Dvorak's
non-American quartet,

00:14:42.170 --> 00:14:44.930
do we call it a Czech quartet or?

00:14:44.930 --> 00:14:49.950
So let's just begin by
listening to the opening

00:14:49.950 --> 00:14:51.250
of the first movement here.

00:14:54.510 --> 00:15:46.040
[ Music ]

00:15:46.040 --> 00:15:49.800
So there would seem to be to me
absolutely nothing national in it,

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:52.060
no spices, no paprika

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:54.930
to make Hungarian chicken
or American spices.

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:57.510
And it uses a kind of standard.

00:15:57.510 --> 00:16:06.110
[ Music ]

00:16:06.110 --> 00:16:08.720
So to go back and forth
between major and minor,

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:10.590
but that's something
that Schubert does.

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:15.270
This seems to be very
much within the larger,

00:16:15.270 --> 00:16:19.900
particularly German quartet
tradition of the composers

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:24.840
that Dvorak loved and Mozart
and Haydn, especially Schubert.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:30.050
Mozart, I mean Dvorak was quite
reticent, he wasn't a literary man.

00:16:30.050 --> 00:16:33.450
But one of the only articles
he wrote was about Schubert,

00:16:33.450 --> 00:16:35.880
so he was very much a
Schubertian, Schumann.

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:38.520
Certainly Brahms, it's
well-known that these --

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:41.060 position:56%
the quartet was dedicated to Brahms.

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:45.610
And Brahms of course, clucked a bit
and said, well young man, you know,

00:16:45.610 --> 00:16:48.960 position:56%
I like this piece okay, but you
really need to be a bit more careful

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:53.920
around the edges and they had that
kind of relationship that it's,

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:58.030
you know, I don't know what
it says about Brahms to say

00:16:58.030 --> 00:17:01.150
that Dvorak might have
been his favorite composer,

00:17:01.150 --> 00:17:03.930
but he would still
wag his finger at him.

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:07.950
But they had an extraordinary
relationship and I think he wanted

00:17:07.950 --> 00:17:11.940
to write -- Dvorak very much
wanted to write a quartet

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:14.160
that fit into that tradition.

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:21.450
Now the quartet is not without
sort of obligatory genuflections

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:24.910
to the worlds of nation
and nationality.

00:17:24.910 --> 00:17:33.510
You know, the second movement
is a polka or ala polka.

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:46.060
[ Music ]

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:49.520
So this is just at the moment
where Dvorak is figuring himself

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:53.440
out about how he's going to
bill himself, how he's going

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:59.010
to portray himself, particularly
in the German-speaking lands.

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:04.170
This is almost like a little bit
of one of his Slavonic dances

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:06.320
that sort of intrudes into this.

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:10.940
But you know you also get
one of the wonderful moments

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:16.160
in this quartet is the trio,
the middle section of this polka

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:20.320
where everything stops
and you get a little kind

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:25.510
of Christmas pastoral absolutely
exquisite sort of rural moment.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:41.050
[ Music ]

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:45.250
So there's a bit of a clash and
a wonderful one in this piece

00:18:45.250 --> 00:18:50.030
between this sort of darker D
minor opening movement of polka

00:18:50.030 --> 00:18:53.490
and then the polka
opening up into sort

00:18:53.490 --> 00:18:57.760
of a little almost
Beethovenian image of this kind

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:03.420
of rural bliss that's just really,
you know, an extraordinary thing

00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:06.750
and I think it's something
that Brahms noticed as well.

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:13.190
You can hear Dvorak's debts
to some of his predecessors,

00:19:13.190 --> 00:19:16.000
particularly in the last movement.

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:30.590
Oops sorry.

00:19:33.070 --> 00:19:37.750 position:56%
That's the lea, I skipped the second
movement and that's my favorite one.

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:40.970
So let me talk about the second
movement, I mean the slow movement.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:43.490
The slow movement, the
adagio is again one

00:19:43.490 --> 00:19:47.200
of Dvorak's great movements.

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:52.930
It's absolutely I think devoid
of any kind of nationalizing,

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:57.360
any sort of genuflections
in those directions.

00:19:57.360 --> 00:20:03.950
And it pursues a formal structure
that many composers employed,

00:20:03.950 --> 00:20:11.090
but Dvorak I think to particular
effect, which is begins as a kind

00:20:11.090 --> 00:20:15.540
of romance, as a highly
expressive romance and then

00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:20.250
as the movement goes on it simply
gets more and more expressive

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:25.160
until the very middle of the piece
where it kind -- where it explodes.

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:27.000
But here's the opening of it.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:21:06.040
[ Music ]

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:10.100
So setting this tone
of kind of reflection,

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:13.580
prayerfulness, but also romance.

00:21:13.580 --> 00:21:17.920
So there are kind of two middles
as it gets more and more intense.

00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:24.510
The first one almost suggests a
kind of Spanish harmonic quality.

00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:57.040
[ Music ]

00:21:57.040 --> 00:21:58.990
So this is also this
is a kind of reference

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:02.520
to something quite exotic
Dvorak loved to do that.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:08.510
Here's a kind of similar passage
from his famous violin romance.

00:22:08.510 --> 00:22:24.080
[ Music ]

00:22:24.080 --> 00:22:25.780
So not very Czech right.

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:29.980 position:56%
I mean so there's a lot of
languages that Dvorak is pulling on.

00:22:29.980 --> 00:22:34.440
There's Brahms in the high style,
there's Czechness [phonetic]

00:22:34.440 --> 00:22:39.710
when he needs a polka and
there's Spanish style,

00:22:39.710 --> 00:22:43.150
little pastoral style
taken from early Beethoven.

