00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:13.160
So first let me go over quickly
some of you may know it the story

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:16.860
of Dvorak and the United States.

00:28:16.860 --> 00:28:19.530
He was brought to the United States

00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:22.660
by an extraordinary woman
named Jeanette Thurber.

00:28:22.660 --> 00:28:27.540
Jeanette Thurber was a
brilliant woman who decided

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:32.840
that the United States should
try to hold its own with Europe

00:28:32.840 --> 00:28:34.330
in terms of musical culture.

00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:39.200
She started an opera company,
she believed in opera in English.

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:43.050
She had the for its
time or maybe honestly

00:28:43.050 --> 00:28:48.410
for any time the astonishing
idea that anybody should be able

00:28:48.410 --> 00:28:53.000
to study music regardless of
their background, their color,

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.550
their economic level, their
religion, their gender.

00:28:56.550 --> 00:29:01.480
She wanted to create an institution
that would be open to all.

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:06.380
And she fastened on Dvorak
because she knew that Dvorak came

00:29:06.380 --> 00:29:09.380
from humble circumstances
and thought

00:29:09.380 --> 00:29:11.820
that he would make
a marvelous leader

00:29:11.820 --> 00:29:15.410
for her national conservatory,
which she started

00:29:15.410 --> 00:29:20.870
on East 17th Street now the site
of Washington Irving High School,

00:29:20.870 --> 00:29:23.860
but formerly the site of
the National Conservatory.

00:29:23.860 --> 00:29:31.110 position:56%
She paid Dvorak what we already know
was a princely wage in 1893, 92,

00:29:31.110 --> 00:29:34.020
93 to come to the United
States and the reasons

00:29:34.020 --> 00:29:38.150
that she wanted Dvorak
were I think threefold.

00:29:38.150 --> 00:29:44.050
The first again, she wanted
to create an institution

00:29:44.050 --> 00:29:47.490
in the United States that
would be of such high quality

00:29:47.490 --> 00:29:51.100
that students would not feel
the need to go to Europe

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:53.320
to finish their musical education.

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:58.590
So she thought well let's get
the best people in the world,

00:29:58.590 --> 00:30:03.310
let's use American know-how and
especially money to hire some

00:30:03.310 --> 00:30:06.450
of the best people so that
people didn't have to go abroad.

00:30:06.450 --> 00:30:08.860
The second as I've
already mentioned,

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:14.000
she wanted to have an
institution which she felt was true

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.820
to the principles of this country,
of the ideals of this country

00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:21.210
that would be open to everybody.

00:30:21.210 --> 00:30:26.590
And if people couldn't pay their
tuition would be paid it didn't

00:30:26.590 --> 00:30:28.480
matter what their background was.

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:31.460
So she had many women students,
African-American students,

00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:34.670
students from all kinds
of backgrounds.

00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:38.170
But the third thing she wanted and
this is really where Dvorak came

00:30:38.170 --> 00:30:41.430
in whether it's a wrongheaded
idea from the get-go

00:30:41.430 --> 00:30:45.250
or not is something you
all can decide over time,

00:30:45.250 --> 00:30:46.640 position:56%
I think there are many perspectives.

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:52.080
But she wanted a music that would
sound American the way she thought

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:55.410
Russian music was Russian,
Hungarian music was Hungarian

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:57.480
and Czech music was Czech.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:31:01.470
She wanted something that would be
an equivalent and she brought it --

00:31:01.470 --> 00:31:05.770
you can view it as an
experiment that she's a scientist

00:31:05.770 --> 00:31:09.860
and she brought Dvorak
over as an experiment.

00:31:09.860 --> 00:31:11.790
By the way, I'm just
reminded as I'm speaking one

00:31:11.790 --> 00:31:14.990 position:56%
of the great science-fiction stories
I read was by is called a Work

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:19.690
of Art by James Bliss, it's
online you can read it.

00:31:19.690 --> 00:31:23.080
And hundreds of years or
maybe a thousand years

00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:28.030 position:56%
in the future I can't quite remember
they recreate Ricard Strauss

00:31:28.030 --> 00:31:32.820
out of some scientific principle so
that he can write works for them,

00:31:32.820 --> 00:31:36.330
but he can't because
he's out of his time.

00:31:36.330 --> 00:31:39.600
But this is kind of an experiment
she's bringing Dvorak to America,

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:44.250
she's saying okay, I'm going
to give you all kinds of queues

00:31:44.250 --> 00:31:47.910
and let's see what it means
to write American music.

00:31:47.910 --> 00:31:55.460
So Dvorak arrives in the
United States October 1892.

00:31:55.460 --> 00:32:01.550
If you do your math October
12, 1892 is not the 500th,

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:04.970
