where and Dvorak love those sort

00:41:49.730 --> 00:41:52.850
of nothing really happens, it's not

00:41:52.850 --> 00:41:55.710
as if you have a sense
of harmonic movement.

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:59.130
It's as if the lights
shifted a little bit.

00:41:59.130 --> 00:42:03.110
And so you get this and this
is written I think in the --

00:42:03.110 --> 00:42:06.160
at least partially in
this Schubertian sort

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:07.680
of heavenly length traditionally.

00:42:07.680 --> 00:42:11.090
It just really goes on and
on, there's no real pause.

00:42:11.090 --> 00:42:14.280
It just keeps unfolding
and intensifying

00:42:14.280 --> 00:42:18.510
in a way that's really
quite marvelous.

00:42:18.510 --> 00:42:22.190
It has the quality of lament to it

00:42:22.190 --> 00:42:24.430
and several times people
have referred to it

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:26.560
as a kind of Indian lament.

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:30.690
And that's one of the chapters of
Dvorak's time in the United States,

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:35.520
which is most poorly understood
and I don't know if we ever will.

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:38.220
Well when Dvorak's
first great biographer

00:42:38.220 --> 00:42:42.130
in English John Clapham
wrote about Dvorak's time

00:42:42.130 --> 00:42:47.210
in Iowa he became puzzled
because there was a reference

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:53.660
to the Kickapoo and he wanted to
know what tribe the Kickapoo were.

00:42:53.660 --> 00:42:56.780
But in fact, there was
no Kickapoo tribe there,

00:42:56.780 --> 00:43:00.220
there was something called
the Kickapoo Medicine Show

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:02.090
that Dvorak heard.

00:43:02.090 --> 00:43:08.420
And the Kickapoo Medicine Show
was a kind of Pan American music,

00:43:08.420 --> 00:43:11.140
it had an African-American
banjo player,

00:43:11.140 --> 00:43:14.590 position:56%
it had people from different tribes,
it was a little bit of a show.

00:43:14.590 --> 00:43:17.620
So we really don't
know what he heard.

00:43:17.620 --> 00:43:22.110
But it's likely that the
he was taken by this,

00:43:22.110 --> 00:43:24.990
although his reactions
to it were ambivalent.

00:43:24.990 --> 00:43:27.730 position:56%
We don't know quite what he thought.

00:43:27.730 --> 00:43:32.490
But in any case, there was a
tendency to tie Dvorak to this.

00:43:32.490 --> 00:43:35.520
But there's also another thing
in this particular movement

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:39.300
which is redolent of Dvorak.

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:42.310
Dvorak had something of
a reputation of being

00:43:42.310 --> 00:43:49.820
in unproblematic happy Czech
and yet, his works are filled

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:53.110
with funerals and funeral marches.

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:57.970
The symphonic poems almost all
have funeral marches in the middle

00:43:57.970 --> 00:44:02.520
of the Largo of the New World
Symphony, there's a passage based

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:06.670
on the death of Minnehaha
from the song of Hiawatha.

00:44:06.670 --> 00:44:12.870
The cello concerto slow movement
has a funeral interruption

00:44:12.870 --> 00:44:20.720
and at the very end of this
movement there's some kind of --

00:44:20.720 --> 00:44:27.380 position:56%
the constant sound which has gone on
and on for five or six minutes stops

00:44:27.380 --> 00:44:30.510
and we have this kind
of funeral march.

00:44:30.510 --> 00:45:01.040
[ Music ]

00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:06.620 position:56%
So some kind of prairie funeral
being enacted in the course of this.

00:45:06.620 --> 00:45:11.610
Now we don't actually know
exactly what to do with pieces

00:45:11.610 --> 00:45:16.820
of music right because, you know,
you have this inner longing,

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:26.200
sighing, deep maybe even anguish
and then here's the next movement.

00:45:26.200 --> 00:45:30.810
What are you supposed to do with
that, nobody really knows right.

00:45:30.810 --> 00:45:34.160
I mean it really is an
astonishing contrast

00:45:34.160 --> 00:45:40.060
and this movement is also
another way that Dvorak tried

00:45:40.060 --> 00:45:43.050
to make American music and
maybe he can be forgiven

00:45:43.050 --> 00:45:45.080
for doing it too obviously.

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:49.000
So again, here's the opening.

00:45:51.510 --> 00:46:08.190
[ Music ]

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:11.510
So that passage there.

00:46:11.510 --> 00:46:16.040
[ Music ]

00:46:16.040 --> 00:46:20.160
We're told that Dvorak while
he was writing this sort

00:46:20.160 --> 00:46:25.730
of became a little bit obsessed
with the sound of black bird

00:46:25.730 --> 00:46:30.040
or with red wings or red wing, you
know, we're not quite sure what.

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:32.000
But we pretty much think it's this.

00:46:36.510 --> 00:46:47.060
[ Birds Singing ]

00:46:47.060 --> 00:46:49.840
Scarlett [inaudible] and
that Dvorak was trying.

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:53.390
One of the ways that he tried
to make his music American was

00:46:53.390 --> 00:46:55.660
to stick an American bird in it

00:46:55.660 --> 00:46:58.040
because how can you
say it's not American.

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:01.620
And so we hear this in
various different times.

00:47:01.620 --> 00:47:05.510
So here's another one.

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:18.040
[ Music ]

00:47:18.040 --> 00:47:21.420 position:56%
Those are the robin and the bluebird
taken out of a book of bird songs

00:47:21.420 --> 00:47:25.510
and stuck right into
the New World Symphony.

00:47:25.510 --> 00:47:32.040
[ Music ]

00:47:32.040 --> 00:47:35.990
Magpies and blue jays in the
scherzo of the New World Symphony.

00:47:35.990 --> 00:47:41.200
So Dvorak decided that in
his scherzo he would stick

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:44.140
in the sounds of this tanager.

00:47:44.140 --> 00:47:46.690
And so we have this
sort of full picture.

00:47:46.690 --> 00:47:50.940
We have the sadness of the prairie,
we have the energy of coming

00:47:50.940 --> 00:47:53.980
into the country and
then we have these sort

00:47:53.980 --> 00:47:56.080
of extraordinary bird songs.

00:47:56.080 --> 00:47:59.180
The last movement combines
a lot of these things

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:02.510
because we have a kind
of celebratory.

00:48:02.510 --> 00:48:13.040
[ Music ]

00:48:13.040 --> 00:48:14.700
So again, what are these sounds?

00:48:14.700 --> 00:48:17.000
It's these simple sounds.

00:48:18.960 --> 00:48:22.230
The kinds of things he
was hearing in black music

00:48:22.230 --> 00:48:23.530
that he was sometimes hearing

00:48:23.530 --> 00:48:26.850
in Native American music these
little phrases that come together,

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:32.260
but also an extraordinary
sense of lyrical expansiveness.

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:35.510
This is the second theme
in the last movement.

00:48:35.510 --> 00:48:50.040
[ Music ]

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:54.290
I mean, you know, you can name
70 film scores that come right

00:48:54.290 --> 00:48:57.250
out of this sound, which was
a very influential sound.

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:59.280
But then in the middle
of the movement,

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:00.580
middle of the movements sorry,

00:49:00.580 --> 00:49:05.510
exact middle of movement he does
something a little bit unusual.

00:49:05.510 --> 00:49:34.190
[ Music ]

00:49:34.190 --> 00:49:39.130
So he has kind of reminiscence
of the mood of the slow movement,

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:44.670
the second movement kind of comes
back in a celebratory last movement

00:49:44.670 --> 00:49:49.460
to once more sort of suggest
a more reflective mode.

00:49:49.460 --> 00:49:54.410
You know, writing a piece
of music is both someone

00:49:54.410 --> 00:49:58.140
like Dvorak quite natural,
but also extremely complex.

00:49:58.140 --> 00:50:00.970
You're always asking how much
of this do I do before I do some

00:50:00.970 --> 00:50:03.970
of that and what's the
effect of that going to be.

00:50:03.970 --> 00:50:06.380
And if I want to say
this, how do I say it.

00:50:06.380 --> 00:50:09.070
If what I really want to say is
the middle how do I surround it

00:50:09.070 --> 00:50:10.370
with various parts.

00:50:10.370 --> 00:50:16.300 position:56%
And in a piece like this just as I
think Mrs. Thurber was experimenting

00:50:16.300 --> 00:50:20.330
with what it meant to try
to make American music.

00:50:20.330 --> 00:50:24.830
Dvorak was using all these new
ideas combined with his old ones

00:50:24.830 --> 00:50:29.190
because the people who don't
like this notion of Dvorak trying

00:50:29.190 --> 00:50:34.890
to write American music will always
point out that Dvorak used some

00:50:34.890 --> 00:50:40.030
of these same ideas when he was
in the Czech lands, in Bohemia.

00:50:40.030 --> 00:50:45.810
That would be like saying
somebody who comes over from Japan

00:50:45.810 --> 00:50:51.280
to paint the American West
isn't painting the American West

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:53.800
because they're using a tree.

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:56.840
Well I mean everyone
has a basic technique,

00:50:56.840 --> 00:51:01.150
you don't lose your
basic technique simply

00:51:01.150 --> 00:51:04.310
because you find new inspirations.

00:51:04.310 --> 00:51:06.570
But what Dvorak tried
to do I think was

00:51:06.570 --> 00:51:11.840
to quite consciously do what
Mrs. Thurber wanted him to do,

00:51:11.840 --> 00:51:15.530
which was again to
create an American music

00:51:15.530 --> 00:51:17.310
that was like his Czech music.

00:51:17.310 --> 00:51:22.660
I think and this is crude that she
thought he had made Czech music

00:51:22.660 --> 00:51:26.970
by taking our basic model, a
German model really of music

00:51:26.970 --> 00:51:30.420
and putting Czechisms [phonetic]
in she sort of wanted him to take

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:34.260
out the Czechisms and
put in Americanisms.

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:37.420
And one of the ways he did that
was by not putting in Czechisms.

00:51:37.420 --> 00:51:41.010
So there's very little in any
of these American period works

00:51:41.010 --> 00:51:44.520
that even by name or deed
or sound suggest polka,

00:51:44.520 --> 00:51:48.290
suggest anything other
than American-style.

00:51:48.290 --> 00:51:52.300
But there's every evidence
that Dvorak believed in this

00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:54.280
and that he believed
that he should try

00:51:54.280 --> 00:51:58.690
to show American composers what
it meant to write American music.

00:51:58.690 --> 00:52:00.760
Well whether you want to
take the view of some people

00:52:00.760 --> 00:52:04.700
and say this led directly
to Gershwin, to Copeland

00:52:04.700 --> 00:52:08.010 position:56%
and to Duke Ellington as my
colleague, Maurice Perez, would say.

00:52:08.010 --> 00:52:09.850
Or whether you're a
little bit more skeptical

00:52:09.850 --> 00:52:14.550 position:56%
about how Dvorak's American language
was received, there's no doubt

00:52:14.550 --> 00:52:18.730
that he tried to do it and the best
proof of that was a remark he made

00:52:18.730 --> 00:52:26.250
in some anger to his student and
amanuensis, Yosef Kovarik she said,

00:52:26.250 --> 00:52:29.570
this is -- after he'd written
these pieces he came back.

00:52:29.570 --> 00:52:33.910
New World Symphony was premiered,
all kinds of angry cries there's no

00:52:33.910 --> 00:52:35.210
such thing as American music

00:52:35.210 --> 00:52:37.010
who do you think you are
you don't know anything.

00:52:37.010 --> 00:52:39.730
You come from Bohemia you're
going to teach us, go away.

00:52:39.730 --> 00:52:44.010
And Dvorak wrote, you know,

00:52:44.010 --> 00:52:48.160
they call me an American
composer, you know, but I'm not.

00:52:48.160 --> 00:52:50.440
I just tried to show
them what it would be

00:52:50.440 --> 00:52:53.960
like to be an American composer,
but I'm not doing that anymore.

00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:56.820
And I think by and large
he stopped doing it.

00:52:56.820 --> 00:53:00.880 position:56%
So the fact that he was doing is the
evidence in effect that he stopped.

00:53:00.880 --> 00:53:04.390
So these again, are
extraordinary pieces.

00:53:04.390 --> 00:53:08.200
Whether you choose to call
this one the American,

00:53:08.200 --> 00:53:12.810
Martinu is the Parisian and
Dvorak's earlier one the Habsburg

00:53:12.810 --> 00:53:16.940
because it seems to combine all
the styles that you would want

00:53:16.940 --> 00:53:21.080
to have together or you
just simply think of them

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:24.840
as extraordinary pieces of music
doesn't really matter much.

00:53:24.840 --> 00:53:29.460
But what does matter is the kinds
of intensity and combinations

00:53:29.460 --> 00:53:31.520
and contrast that you
get in these pieces.

00:53:31.520 --> 00:53:33.320
Thank you very much.

