00:53:59.090 --> 00:54:04.820
&gt;&gt; Back to Martinu, who were
some of his musical influences,

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:10.130
if any because he doesn't really
sound much like anyone else?

00:54:10.130 --> 00:54:12.590
&gt;&gt; Michael Beckerman: Well
I mean that's, you know,

00:54:12.590 --> 00:54:14.620
I mean the best thing I've
read about influence not

00:54:14.620 --> 00:54:17.530 position:56%
that I really understand it is that
the reason it's so difficult to talk

00:54:17.530 --> 00:54:22.160
about it because the most profound
influences act over a long period

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:25.970
from a great distance, so it's
always tricky to pick them up.

00:54:25.970 --> 00:54:29.800
But I think there are several,

00:54:29.800 --> 00:54:36.500
I mean I think he was very much
taken with his Dvorak school.

00:54:36.500 --> 00:54:40.330
You know, I think in many ways even
though his music sounds different

00:54:40.330 --> 00:54:47.000 position:56%
in terms of the kinds of pieces that
he wrote he chose to follow that.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:50.990
He studied with Josef Suk,
you know, Dvorak's son-in-law

00:54:50.990 --> 00:54:55.970
and I think again, I think he
was influenced by this tradition.

00:54:55.970 --> 00:55:00.780
I Again, it's tricky to sort of
make generalizations like this

00:55:00.780 --> 00:55:02.580
because they stick
and they ought not to.

00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:08.370
But, you know, this was a
tradition of non-virtuosos.

00:55:08.370 --> 00:55:10.830
You know, Suk himself even
though he was the leader

00:55:10.830 --> 00:55:13.950
of the Bohemian Quartet
was a second violinist.

00:55:13.950 --> 00:55:16.080
Martinu was a second violinist.

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:18.200
Dvorak was a violist.

00:55:18.200 --> 00:55:22.560
And I think something of
that kind of workman-like,

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:26.400
somewhat modest part of
the tradition comes out

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:28.520
and I think he knew those works.

00:55:28.520 --> 00:55:32.440
I think he was interested in
Janacek and I think that comes

00:55:32.440 --> 00:55:35.160
out sometimes in the operas.

00:55:35.160 --> 00:55:38.990
I was, I mean the person
I spoke to most

00:55:38.990 --> 00:55:41.070
about this was a little
trick was Rudolf [inaudible],

00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:46.220
who was a student of Janacek's and
a very good friend of Martinu's.

00:55:46.220 --> 00:55:50.800
And now Martinu also
was I think very taken

00:55:50.800 --> 00:55:53.580
with Albert Roussell
and the French style.

00:55:53.580 --> 00:55:58.150 position:56%
He studied with Roussell and he was,
you know, active and influenced.

00:55:58.150 --> 00:56:02.240
There's an extremely strong
Stravinskian influence in a lot

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:05.480
of pieces from that period.

00:56:05.480 --> 00:56:12.040
But I think sort of the Martinu
style that he cultivates really

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:16.220
from the 1930's on, I mean again
it draws on Czech folklore,

00:56:16.220 --> 00:56:20.660
it draws on Slovak music, it draws
on Czech pastoral traditions.

00:56:20.660 --> 00:56:24.900
He richly draws on a lot, but I
don't think there is that kind

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:26.630
of influence I think you're right.

00:56:26.630 --> 00:56:29.800
