00:56:29.800 --> 00:56:34.660
&gt;&gt; Was there any overlap
with Smetana's lifetime

00:56:34.660 --> 00:56:39.330 position:56%
and was there any influence with the
[inaudible] in any of Dvorak's work?

00:56:39.330 --> 00:56:43.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Beckerman:
Yeah, I think certainly,

00:56:43.840 --> 00:56:48.290
I mean Smetana was unavoidable
to Dvorak for many reasons.

00:56:48.290 --> 00:56:51.700
One of greatest was that
he played under Dvorak,

00:56:51.700 --> 00:56:54.900
I mean Smetana's baton for, you
know, played as second violinist

00:56:54.900 --> 00:56:58.710 position:56%
and Smetana was the conductor of the
orchestra of the provisional theater

00:56:58.710 --> 00:57:02.840
and so he obviously learned an
enormous amount from Smetana.

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:06.200
You know and I think
he admired Smetana.

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:13.750
There was a certain level of
rivalry Dvorak Slavonic dances were

00:57:13.750 --> 00:57:17.330
extraordinarily successful
and it sort

00:57:17.330 --> 00:57:22.390
of illustrates a little bit you
know the Harold Bloom anxiety

00:57:22.390 --> 00:57:28.550
of influence because people
often like to tell happy stories,

00:57:28.550 --> 00:57:32.350
people often like to tell happy
stories about the relationship

00:57:32.350 --> 00:57:38.410
between composers, how they help
each other and Haydn loves Mozart.

00:57:38.410 --> 00:57:43.340
But you know Bloom thinks of
this more as mortal combat

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:45.230
and I don't know how mortal it was,

00:57:45.230 --> 00:57:48.440
but when Dvorak had
this enormous success

00:57:48.440 --> 00:57:51.630
with the Slavonic dances
Smetana kind of shook his finger

00:57:51.630 --> 00:57:54.680
and wrote a series
of quite wonderful --

00:57:54.680 --> 00:57:55.980
not as popular as Dvorak,

00:57:55.980 --> 00:57:59.870
but wonderful pieces called the
Czech dances because he felt

00:57:59.870 --> 00:58:03.090
that Dvorak's dances
were not Czech enough.

00:58:03.090 --> 00:58:07.630
And he wanted to show him what
it meant to write Czech music

00:58:07.630 --> 00:58:13.010 position:56%
for Smetana was to apply the highest
level intellectual traditions

00:58:13.010 --> 00:58:17.680
of modern music, but somehow
referring to local things.

00:58:17.680 --> 00:58:21.460
So and I think he felt
Dvorak was too international.

00:58:21.460 --> 00:58:27.400
And unfortunately, this became a
very ugly battle not between Dvorak

00:58:27.400 --> 00:58:30.260
and Smetana who were mostly gone

00:58:30.260 --> 00:58:34.250
by the time the biggest battles
erupted, but it's well-known

00:58:34.250 --> 00:58:37.580
that the Smetana's
champion was a kind

00:58:37.580 --> 00:58:43.270 position:56%
of a mustachioed intellectual
villain and his name was [inaudible]

00:58:43.270 --> 00:58:47.580
who gained more power than a
musicologist should ever have.

00:58:47.580 --> 00:58:51.140
By the time the communists took
power he became the Minister

00:58:51.140 --> 00:58:52.440
of Culture.

00:58:52.440 --> 00:58:55.570
But long before that he has
basically taught generations

00:58:55.570 --> 00:59:01.650
of students to worship Smetana and
[inaudible] and to revile Dvorak

00:59:01.650 --> 00:59:06.210
as a kind of bloated, cosmopolitan

00:59:06.210 --> 00:59:09.690
who simply whatever good qualities
he might've had he was simply

00:59:09.690 --> 00:59:12.850
showing Czech music
the wrong way forward.

00:59:12.850 --> 00:59:17.510
So these kinds of things intrude
even now into the literature.

